  "response": "The average age of PhD graduates varies across different academic disciplines. Here's a general overview based on U.S. data:\n\n1. Humanities: Typically around 35-40 years old\n2. Social Sciences: Around 34-38 years old\n3. Natural Sciences: Around 30-35 years old\n4. Engineering: Around 32-36 years old\n5. Life Sciences: Around 32-36 years old\n6. Computer Science: Around 30-34 years old\n7. Mathematical Sciences: Around 30-35 years old\n\nThese are approximate ranges and can vary depending on factors like:\n- Individual program requirements\n- Full-time vs. part-time study\n- Prior work experience\n- Funding and research opportunities\n- Specific university and department\n\nThe total time to complete a PhD typically ranges from 4-7 years after obtaining a master's degree, which contributes to the variation in graduate ages.\n\nFor precise, current data, I recommend consulting recent national education statistics or specific disciplinary research reports.",
